as a footnote that appears to be cut off.\n\nThe footnote clarifies that the loose coupling benefit is inherent to DI containers themselves, not just auto-injection, so even without autowire you get this advantage by using a DI container. This is more of an educational note than an implementation constraint, but it's worth flagging as a minor gap in the knowledge file since it provides important context for understanding when to use auto-injection versus not.\n\nSection s4 covers property elements nesting component elements, which is useful for components used by only one parent, the nested component naming format using dot notation like \"parent.child\", and the configuration example demonstrating this pattern.\n\nSection s5 covers the key-value pair syntax with '=' delimiter, special character handling including how spaces and colons are treated differently than in .properties files, comment syntax with '#' and escape sequences, line continuation with backslash, and the warning about the problematic pattern of placing comments before a backslash. The knowledge file has all of this covered.\n\nNow I'm checking the escape character handling more carefully—specifically whether the knowledge file captures that you need to prepend a backslash to include a literal backslash in keys or values. Looking at the source material, it seems the knowledge file's table covers the basic escape functionality but may not explicitly document how to escape the backslash character itself, even though this detail appears in the source for each special character type. I'm noticing the knowledge file is missing details about escaping backslashes themselves, and also doesn't mention that tokens after the third delimiter are ignored—both are behavioral specifics worth noting. デリミタは`=`のみで、空白やコロンも文字列の一部として扱う。キーと値は前後の空白をトリミングするが、`=`を含めたい場合は`\\\\=`でエスケープする。また、3番目以降の`=`区切り文字は無視され、キーは大文字小文字を区別する。例えば` A B `という文字列は`A B`にトリミングされる。\n\nドキュメント全体の構造を確認すると、RST形式で複数のセクションが定義されており、アンダースコア文字の種類によってヘッダレベルが決ま